Poverty is a near universal condition in much of the world. One
billion people live on less than one dollar a day.

In 1992, World Bank president Lewis Preston issued a directive to link
loan volume to the strength of a country's efforts to fight poverty.
This initiative forms part of a new drive to make poverty alleviation
the bank's central mission in the 1990's.

John Hatch, founder of the non-profit Foundation for International
Community Assistance developed a concept of using small revolving
loans to poor women to finance their private enterprise. The interest
rate would be between 1 percent to 3 percent.</SUM>
